   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="transcription">
            <p>
<lb corresp="#b5"/><w>wäśśitsuneyā</w></p>
         </div>
         <div type="translation">
            <p><choice corresp="#b5"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">with ease</seg></seg></choice></p>
         </div>
         <div type="comments">
            <p><note type="lingcomment">The form is a perlative singular. Schmidt (<bibl><title corresp="ref:wille2000"/><citedRange>18</citedRange></bibl>) rather reads <hi>wäśśitsune[y]ā(<hi rend="underline">ṣ</hi><hi rend="subscript">\</hi>)</hi>, apparently confusing the perlative in <hi>-a</hi> with the ablative in <hi>-ṣ</hi>. As pointed out by Schmidt in a later publication (<bibl><title corresp="ref:schmidtkt1999b"/><citedRange>284</citedRange></bibl>), <hi>wäśśitsune</hi> is an abstract derived from an adjective <hi>wäśśi</hi> that is actually attested in <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-yqiii8"/>: a7 <hi>mā täm wäśśi ānant märkampalṣināp prucca(mñe)</hi> 'It is not easy, Ānanda, (to describe?) the advantage of the law'. A connection with TA <hi>wäṣt</hi> 'double' as suggested by <bibl><title corresp="ref:jietal1998"/><citedRange>180</citedRange></bibl> is formally attractive, but semantically far from obvious.</note><note type="philcomment">Glosses Skt. <hi>sugamatvān</hi> (abl.sg.; for <hi>sugamatvāt</hi> in sandhi before <hi>n</hi>) 'with easiness'.</note></p>
         </div>
